Fusion, which came out of stealth mode in November 2024. Other significant roun\n\nSource: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JT-60\nTitle: JT-60 - Wikipedia\nSnippet: JT-60SA under construction in 2016. JT-60SA is the successor to JT-60U, operating as a satellite to ITER as described by the Broader Approach Agreement. It is a fully superconducting tokamak with flexible components that can be adjusted to find optimized plasma configurations and address key physics issues. [33] Assembly began in January 2013 and was completed in March 2020. After a major ...\nContent: JT-60 - Wikipedia Jump to content From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia Japanese tokamak This article is about the tokamak. For the school district, see Miami-Yoder School District JT-60 . This scientific article needs additional citations to secondary or tertiary sources . Help add sources such as review articles, monographs, or textbooks. Please also establish the relevance for any primary research articles cited. Unsourced or poorly sourced material may be challenged and removed. ( April 2025 ) ( Learn how and when to remove this message ) JT-60 Japan Torus-60 Device type Tokamak Location Naka , Ibaraki Prefecture , Japan Affiliation Japan Atomic Energy Agency Technical specifications Major radius 3.4 m (11 ft) Minor radius 1.0 m (3 ft 3 in) Plasma volume 90 m 3 Magnetic field 4 T (40,000 G) (toroidal) Discharge duration 65 s History Year(s) of operation 1985–2010 Preceded by JFT-2M Succeeded by JT-60SA Related devices TFTR Links Website www .qst .go .jp /site /jt60-english / JT-60SA Japan Torus-60 Super Advanced Device type Tokamak Location Naka , Ibaraki Prefecture , Japan Affiliation QST + F4E Technical specifications Discharge duration 100 s History Date(s) of construction 2\n\nSource: https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1741-4326/ad34e4\nTitle: Recent progress of JT-60SA project toward plasma operation\nSnippet: Superconducting (SC) tokamak JT-60SA plays an essential role in fusion research and development by supporting and complementing the ITER project, providing directions to the DEMO design activity and fostering next generation scientists and engineers. Since the short circuit incident at the terminal joints of equilibrium field coil #1 during the integrated commissioning (IC) in March 2021, both ...\nContent: Radware Bot Manager Captcha We apologize for the inconvenience... To ensure we keep this website safe, please can you confirm you are a human by ticking the box below. If you are unable to complete the above request please contact us using the below link, providing a screenshot of your experience. https://ioppublishing.org/contacts/ Incident ID: 1cfbbeab-cnvj-4dae-a57b-83503a79de4c\n\nSource: https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1741-4326/ae74e1\nTitle: Overview of first JT-60SA plasma operation and plans in view of ITER ...\nSnippet: Abstract JT-60SA is the world's largest superconducting tokamak in operation jointly built and exploited by Europe and Japan in the framework of the Broader Approach. JT-60SA aims at addressing some of the technological and physics challenges, such as the long pulse steady-state plasma operation at high beta.\nContent: Radware Bot Manager Captcha We apologize for the inconvenience... To ensure we keep this website safe, please can you confirm you are a human by ticking the box below. If you are unable to complete the above request please contact us using the below link, providing a screenshot of your experience. https://ioppublishing.org/contacts/ Incident ID: a157e1c9-cnvj-471b-9ebd-bf88fefe3079\n\nSource: https://www.marketresearch.com/Future-Markets-Inc-v3760/Global-Nuclear-Fusion-Energy-40856583/\nTitle: The Global Nuclear Fusion Energy Market 2025-2045\nSnippet: Nuclear fusion energy stands at the precipice of commercial viability after decades of scientific pursuit. ... nuclear fission, fusion promises ...\nContent: Just a moment...\n\nSource: https://www.astralcodexten.com/p/your-book-review-the-future-of-fusion\nTitle: Your Book Review: The Future Of Fusion Energy\nSnippet: ... fusion right now, and The Future of ... Q is the ratio of the amount of energy you put into the fuel to the amount of energy produced by fusion.\nContent: Your Book Review: The Future Of Fusion Energy Astral Codex Ten Subscribe Sign in Your Book Review: The Future Of Fusion Energy ... Scott Alexander Jun 17, 2022 143 566 1 Share [ This is one of the finalists in the 2022 book review contest. It’s not by me - it’s by an ACX reader who will remain anonymous until after voting is done, to prevent their identity from influencing your decisions. I’ll be posting about one of these a week for several months. When you’ve read them all, I’ll ask you to vote for a favorite, so remember which ones you liked - SA ] Introduction Fusion is the power which lights the stars. It is the source of all elements heavier than hydrogen in the universe. Wouldn't it be great if we could use and control this power here on Earth? I predict that we will get fusion [1] before 2035 (80%) or 2040 (90%). I am a professional plasma physicist, a fusioneer if you will, so I probably know more about this subject than you, but am likely to overemphasize its importance. The Future of Fusion Energy is the best introduction to fusion that I know. I can confirm that the information it contains is common knowledge among plasma physicists. My parents, who are not physicists [\n\nSource: https://theness.com/neurologicablog/plan-to-build-first-commercial-fusion-reactor/\nTitle: Plan To Build First Commercial Fusion Reactor - NeuroLogica Blog\nSnippet: One company, Commonwealth Fusion Systems, claims it will have completed a fusion reactor capable of producing net energy by “ the early 2030 ...\nContent: Attention Required! | Cloudflare Please enable cookies. Sorry, you have been blocked You are unable to access wpewaf.com Why have I been blocked? This website is using a security service to protect itself from online attacks. The action you just performed triggered the security solution. There are several actions that could trigger this block including submitting a certain word or phrase, a SQL command or malformed data. What can I do to resolve this? You can email the site owner to let them know you were blocked. Please include what you were doing when this page came up and the Cloudflare Ray ID found at the bottom of this page. Cloudflare Ray ID: a0f11f046fb57d8a • Your IP: Click to reveal 138.89.52.82 • Performance & security by Cloudflare\n\nReport:"}], "temperature": 0.4, "response_format": null, "max_tokens": 2000}, "response": "# Nuclear Fusion Energy Progress in 2024: Research Milestones, Investment, and Commercial Outlook\n\n## Introduction\n\nNuclear fusion energy, the process that powers the sun, has long represented humanity's quest for clean, abundant power. Throughout 2024, the fusion sector demonstrated significant momentum across multiple fronts, from sustained plasma achievements to substantial private sector investment. While commercial viability remains years away, the convergence of technological breakthroughs, increased funding, and public-private partnerships has positioned fusion energy as increasingly relevant to addressing global energy challenges.\n\n## Major Research Milestones\n\nA landmark achievement came from France, where a fusion reactor successfully sustained a nuclear reaction for 22 minutes, representing a historic breakthrough in sustained plasma operations (https://glassalmanac.com/french-fusion-reactor-stuns-world-by-sustaining-nuclear-reaction-for-22-minutes-in-breakthrough-energy-milestone/). This accomplishment built upon earlier progress, including the August 8, 2021 achievement at an inertial confinement fusion facility that yielded more than 1.3 megajoules, which was confirmed in reporting from February 15, 2024 (https://www.thesciverse.com/2024/02/nuclear-fusion-energy-breakthrough.html). These milestones demonstrate the potential of fusion fuel, where one gram of deuterium-tritium can generate 90,000 kilowatt-hours of energy—equivalent to 11 tonnes of coal—without producing greenhouse gases (https://glassalmanac.com/french-fusion-reactor-stuns-world-by-sustaining-nuclear-reaction-for-22-minutes-in-breakthrough-energy-milestone/).\n\n## Private Sector Investment and Industry Growth\n\nThe fusion industry experienced substantial financial growth during the period surrounding 2024. According to the Fusion Industry Association's annual Global Fusion Industry Report, the sector raised $2.64 billion in private and public funding in the 12 months leading to July 2025, marking a 178% increase from the previous year and representing the second-highest yearly funding figure since reporting began (https://www.fusionindustryassociation.org/over-2-5-billion-invested-in-fusion-industry-in-past-year/). The number of fusion companies responding to the survey grew to 53, up from 23 in 2021, with total cumulative funding reaching $9.766 billion—a five-fold increase since 2021 (https://www.fusionindustryassociation.org/over-2-5-billion-invested-in-fusion-industry-in-past-year/). Industry reports emphasized that by applying new technology, advanced materials, increased computing power, and private sector ambition, investor-backed companies have demonstrated \"a path to fusion power on a timeline that is relevant to the world's energy challenges\" (https://sciencebusiness.net/sites/default/files/inline-files/FIA_annual+report+2024.pdf).\n\n## Timeline Predictions for Commercial Viability\n\nRegarding commercial deployment timelines, one company, Commonwealth Fusion Systems, has publicly stated it aims to complete a fusion reactor capable of producing net energy by \"the early 2030s\" (https://theness.com/neurologicablog/plan-to-build-first-commercial-fusion-reactor/). More broadly, market analyses indicate that \"nuclear fusion energy stands at the precipice of commercial viability after decades of scientific pursuit\" (https://www.marketresearch.com/Future-Markets-Inc-v3760/Global-Nuclear-Fusion-Energy-40856583/). The acceleration of operational breakthroughs, increased global funding, and international competition—particularly from China—are motivating Western nations to accelerate development timelines (https://medium.com/the-fusion-report/the-elephant-in-the-fusion-room-is-when-313f5cc330fb). Public-private partnerships have been identified as crucial mechanisms to \"rapidly accelerate fusion development by driving new private financial support\" (https://infuse.ornl.gov/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/INFUSE-FIA-2.28.24.pdf).\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe fusion energy sector in 2024 demonstrated tangible progress through sustained plasma achievements, unprecedented private investment growth, and increasingly concrete timelines for commercial deployment. While significant technical challenges remain, the combination of scientific breakthroughs, substantial capital influx, and collaborative frameworks between public research institutions and private companies suggests that fusion energy is transitioning from a distant aspiration to a near-term possibility for addressing global energy needs.", "ts": 1782025093.5474482, "latency_s": 25.31}